            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Here's a Codex-generated analysis (kindly provided by @mitchellh) of the feasibility of replacing `libvterm` with `libghostty-vt`. We didn't really expect a simple drop-in replacement, and we have no need of keeping `terminal.c` compatible with `libvterm`, so the outlook is actually much more positive than this sounds. Definitely looks feasible for a (leisurely) 0.13 target.\n\n---\n## Verdict\n\n1. A direct swap of Neovim’s libvterm fork with libghostty-vt is not currently feasible without behavior regressions. The biggest blockers are missing parser/fallback hooks, missing selection/clipboard callbacks, and mismatch in scrollback ownership/change notifications.\n2. A replacement is still possible as a new Neovim backend (not a drop-in API shim), but it would require an adapter layer plus either feature cuts or new libghostty-vt API surface.\n\n## What Neovim Actually Uses From libvterm\n\n1. Neovim relies on rich screen callbacks for incremental repaint, cursor movement, terminal properties, theme query, and scrollback push/pop/clear in src/nvim/terminal.c, with callback registration in src/nvim/terminal.c and src/nvim/vterm/screen.c.\n2. Neovim depends on fallback parser hooks for OSC/DCS/APC (`TermRequest` and OSC8 handling) in src/nvim/terminal.c, backed by `VTermStateFallbacks` in src/nvim/vterm/vterm_defs.h.\n3. It uses OSC52-style selection callbacks to bridge terminal clipboard writes in src/nvim/terminal.c, src/nvim/terminal.c, and src/nvim/vterm/state.c.\n4. It mutates terminal state directly for cursor shape/blink, palette, and URI pen attrs in src/nvim/terminal.c, src/nvim/terminal.c, and src/nvim/terminal.c, using fork APIs defined in src/nvim/vterm/vterm_defs.h.\n5. It expects integrated input emission via `vterm_output_set_callback` and keyboard/mouse/focus helpers in src/nvim/vterm/vterm.c, src/nvim/terminal.c, src/nvim/terminal.c, src/nvim/terminal.c, and bracketed paste helpers in src/nvim/vterm/keyboard.c.\n\n## What libghostty-vt Covers Well\n\n1. Core terminal lifecycle, mode get/set, VT write, and typed state queries exist in include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h.\n2. Dirty rendering and row/cell iteration are available via render state in include/ghostty/vt/render.h and include/ghostty/vt/render.h.\n3. Input encoding exists for key/mouse/focus in include/ghostty/vt/key/encoder.h, include/ghostty/vt/mouse/encoder.h, and include/ghostty/vt/focus.h, and protocol modes are exposed in include/ghostty/vt/modes.h.\n4. Side-effect callbacks for bell/title/query responses exist in include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h and include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h.\n\n## Hard Gaps (Replacement Blockers)\n\n1. There is no public equivalent to libvterm’s unrecognized/raw OSC/DCS/APC callback flow with fragment + terminator fidelity; ghostty terminal effects are narrower and do not expose parser fallback hooks in include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h and include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h.\n2. There is no terminal-level selection callback API comparable to `vterm_state_set_selection_callbacks`; Neovim uses that heavily in src/nvim/terminal.c and src/nvim/vterm/state.c.\n3. Neovim depends on scrollback push/pop/clear callbacks, while ghostty owns scrollback internally and only offers lookup-style history access; grid-ref is explicitly not for render-loop-grade access in include/ghostty/vt/grid_ref.h and include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h.\n4. Hyperlink parity is incomplete: Neovim tracks URI attrs per-cell in src/nvim/terminal.c, but ghostty cell API only exposes hyperlink presence booleans in include/ghostty/vt/screen.h.\n\n## Medium Gaps (Adaptable, But Non-trivial)\n\n1. No generic settermprop callback in ghostty; Neovim will need post-write diffing of modes/data/render-state instead of event-driven property updates, even though relevant state is queryable in include/ghostty/vt/terminal.h and include/ghostty/vt/render.h.\n2. ~~Palette mutation API equivalent to `vterm_state_set_palette_color` is not present in public ghostty C headers; ghostty exposes palette reads via render-state in include/ghostty/vt/render.h and include/ghostty/vt/render.h, but no corresponding public setter.~~ (already added)\n3. Input model adaptation is required because ghostty uses explicit key/mouse event objects and mouse pixel-space positions in include/ghostty/vt/key/event.h and include/ghostty/vt/mouse/event.h, while Neovim currently emits from keycodes/cell coords.\n4. Bracketed paste helpers are not equivalent out of the box; Neovim currently calls direct begin/end APIs in src/nvim/terminal.c, while ghostty’s public paste API in include/ghostty/vt/paste.h is safety validation, not begin/end emission.\n\n## In-Tree Fork-Specific Features Neovim Leans On\n\n1. Neovim’s fork extends term properties (`THEMEUPDATES`, `SYNCOUTPUT`, cursor shape/blink, etc.) in src/nvim/vterm/vterm_defs.h and processes mode 2026/2031 in src/nvim/vterm/state.c.\n2. Theme query/reply behavior (`CSI ?996 n => ?997;1/2n`) is wired in src/nvim/vterm/state.c and consumed by Neovim in src/nvim/terminal.c.\n3. URI pen attribute support is part of the forked attr model in src/nvim/vterm/vterm_defs.h and used in src/nvim/terminal.c.\n\n## Practical Migration Path\n\n1. Build a Ghostty-native Neovim terminal backend (not a fake `vterm_*` shim), using ghostty terminal + render-state + key/mouse/focus encoders, and keep mode/data diff state inside Neovim.\n2. Accept initial feature cuts for `TermRequest` raw passthrough, OSC52 clipboard bridge, and hyperlink URL metadata unless ghostty adds API for them.\n3. Prioritize upstream `libghostty-vt` additions that would unlock parity: parser fallback hooks, selection callbacks, scrollback changefeed (push/pop or equivalent), hyperlink metadata retrieval, and palette mutation setters.\n---",
